{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"54619d9b-df5e-465d-9930-2ccdd89d002a","content":"`SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` tells the layout to ignore safe-area insets, but it doesn't make the OS actually draw your content behind the system bars. You need **two** things:\n\n### 1. Android — opt into edge-to-edge at the window level\n\nIn `MainActivity.cs` (or via a window lifecycle event):\n\n```csharp\nusing AndroidX.Core.View;\n\nprotected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)\n{\n    base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);\n    WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(Window, false);\n}\n```\n\nThis tells Android to let your app draw behind the status bar and navigation bar. Without it, the system reserves space for those bars regardless of your MAUI layout settings.\n\n### 2. iOS — disable safe area padding\n\nUse the iOS platform-specific on your page:\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage\n    xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n    ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\">\n```\n\n### Putting it together\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage\n    xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n    ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\">\n    <Image Source=\"photo.jpg\"\n           Aspect=\"AspectFill\" />\n</ContentPage>\n```\n\n**TL;DR** — The MAUI layout property alone is not enough. On Android you must call `WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(Window, false)` so the OS stops reserving space for system bars. On iOS, `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"` is the equivalent opt-in.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"da7d277c-b90b-4d6f-84c8-4df91edbe025","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about making content go edge-to-edge in a .NET MAUI app, going behind the status bar and navigation bar. They've tried `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` on the ContentPage but still see padding.\n\nThis is a common .NET MAUI question. In .NET MAUI, to achieve true edge-to-edge content that goes behind system bars, you typically need to:\n\n1. Set `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` on the page (which they've done)\n2. But more importantly, you need to opt into edge-to-edge display mode\n\nIn .NET MAUI / .NET 8+, there's been evolution in how edge-to-edge works. \n\nFor Android specifically, the approach depends on the API level. On Android 15 and newer, edge-to-edge is the default behavior, but you need to explicitly configure the window to not fit system windows using platform-specific APIs. On iOS, there's a similar configuration needed to allow content to extend behind the system bars. The exact implementation varies depending on whether you're targeting .NET 10 or earlier versions of MAUI. Pages don't have a built-in `SafeAreaEdges` property, so the user might be mixing up approaches or using something custom. For actual edge-to-edge rendering in .NET MAUI, iOS needs `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"` in the XAML namespace, while Android requires configuring the window to draw behind system bars through `WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(window, false)` in the MainActivity or via handlers, along with theme settings for translucent status and navigation bars. Setting up edge-to-edge rendering...","outputTokens":1580,"requestId":"D457:2DE6FB:1C2A1A1:1FB0300:6A07BFD1"},"id":"15231240-e4ee-4dce-85fe-d5b6bb618995","timestamp":"2026-05-16T00:53:02.938Z","parentId":"11955dea-29dc-43db-ad74-4272a632b886"}
